# Agent Decision Policy

## Can Decide Without User

Agents may decide when:
- Existing project pattern is clear.
- Change is small and reversible.
- No database schema change.
- No API contract change.
- No authentication or authorization change.
- No billing/payment/tax/legal/business formula change.
- No public export format change.
- No destructive data operation.

## Must Escalate or Create ADR

Agents must create an ADR when:
- Adding new dependency.
- Adding new module.
- Changing architecture.
- Changing database schema.
- Changing API contract.
- Changing auth/permission behavior.
- Changing deployment/build strategy.
- Replacing old implementation.

## Logic Decision Policy

The Logic & Algorithm Engineer may decide:
- Function structure.
- Calculation flow.
- Data normalization strategy.
- Lookup/indexing strategy.
- Loop optimization.
- Test case structure.
- Where calculation should live in the codebase.

The Logic & Algorithm Engineer must not decide alone:
- Business formula source.
- Tax/legal/accounting rule.
- Official construction coefficient.
- Contract-based calculation rule.
- Public report/export format.

If formula or business rule is unclear, the agent must mark it as unresolved instead of guessing.

## Must Not Do

Agents must not:
- Guess business logic.
- Delete existing feature casually.
- Rename public API fields casually.
- Mix framework patterns randomly.
- Add dependency just because it is convenient.
- Build parallel systems.
